WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.160
This is like my favorite subject.

00:00:10.160 --> 00:00:16.160
You know, I spent like 15 years of my life building UIs in the traditional event handler

00:00:16.160 --> 00:00:17.160
way.

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:24.600
It just felt so, so hard that it was almost offensive to me, you know, like that I should

00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:31.799
need to use every single ounce of my brainpower to hold in my head this pretty small dialogue

00:00:31.799 --> 00:00:36.259
in a Windows app, you know, like it's not the most complicated thing in the world.

00:00:36.259 --> 00:00:44.119
And yet I am straining all of my, you know, brain cells to make sure that all these relationships

00:00:44.119 --> 00:00:45.119
are correct.

00:00:45.119 --> 00:00:49.080
It seems like everything you add makes it exponentially more complicated.

00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:50.279
That's exactly right.

00:00:50.279 --> 00:00:52.000
All non-trivial software.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:53.959
This is the number one problem.

00:00:53.959 --> 00:00:56.360
How do we manage the complexity?

00:00:56.360 --> 00:01:00.560
Because everything we add has the potential to interact with everything else.

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:05.199
So what I want to say about this reactive graph issue, where you start out with an input

00:01:05.199 --> 00:01:06.980
and an output, right?

00:01:06.980 --> 00:01:13.320
Not even a reactive in the middle, just input, output, multiple inputs to one output, multiple

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:14.480
outputs to one input.

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:15.480
Sure.

00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:17.000
Like all of that is pretty understandable.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.919
And then you add one or two reactive calculations in the middle, but it doesn't take much for

00:01:22.919 --> 00:01:30.440
that to start becoming very crazily looking, especially when you have multiple levels of

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:31.440
reactive calculations.

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:36.519
I think like a most important thing to understand is that you're not supposed to understand

00:01:36.519 --> 00:01:37.519
the whole graph.

00:01:37.519 --> 00:01:42.599
The goal is not to create a graph that you look at and say, oh, that's definitely right.

00:01:42.599 --> 00:01:48.279
Think of this as the same exact thing with functions in a normal piece of software, a

00:01:48.279 --> 00:01:51.959
normal package, which functions call which other functions.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:53.400
And you could draw a graph with that, right?

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:55.639
You can draw a function called graph.

00:01:55.639 --> 00:01:56.639
And people do.

00:01:56.639 --> 00:01:59.680
There's software that does that for you, helps you make those connections.

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:06.559
The goal is never to be able to look at that entire graph of functions pointing at each

00:02:06.559 --> 00:02:11.119
other and be like, oh, yep, it's right.

00:02:11.119 --> 00:02:12.119
That's not the point.

00:02:12.119 --> 00:02:17.520
If your software is well-written, the point is to be able to look at any one node, any

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:23.039
one node in that graph and prove to yourself that that node is correct.

00:02:23.039 --> 00:02:29.960
To look at one output and just look at the things that are calling into that output.

00:02:29.960 --> 00:02:31.479
Just one level, right?

00:02:31.479 --> 00:02:36.759
Like don't go beyond the arrows that are going directly into that output and say, are those

00:02:36.759 --> 00:02:37.759
correct?

00:02:37.759 --> 00:02:41.520
And if the answer is yes, then you can move on.

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:46.440
You can move on to look at each of the other nodes in the graph.

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:50.240
So the point is not to be able to reason globally.

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:53.240
The point is to be able to reason locally.

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:58.119
This is exactly the same thing that we say about functions, right?

00:02:58.119 --> 00:03:04.160
When you write a function, the goal is not to be able to take the entire rest of your

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:10.240
code base that might indirectly or directly call or be called by a function that's under

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:11.279
a question.

00:03:11.279 --> 00:03:17.479
The goal is to be able to look at this function and to be able to confidently say, if the

00:03:17.479 --> 00:03:22.720
functions that this calls are written correctly, then this logic is correct.

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:28.080
So you need to be able to look at this function and reason about just this function in isolation.

00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:29.360
Now you might be wrong.

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:33.679
Like you might be assuming that those other functions are written correctly and that might

00:03:33.679 --> 00:03:34.960
not be true.

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:40.360
But that problem is a much better problem to have to tackle than the possibility that

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:46.240
all those functions are correctly written and you still don't know if your code is correct.

00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:49.119
Because not only do you have to know that they're correct, but you have to know about

00:03:49.119 --> 00:03:52.399
really subtle interactions that those functions have with each other.

00:03:52.399 --> 00:03:59.399
With reactivity, this is a way that that same quality of I can look at a small piece of

00:03:59.399 --> 00:04:06.919
code and just by knowing that the reactives that are being called, if those just assume

00:04:06.919 --> 00:04:11.479
that those are going to execute at the right time, then this is going to execute at the

00:04:11.479 --> 00:04:12.479
right time.

00:04:12.479 --> 00:04:16.600
If there's something that I'm calling and I don't want to update when it updates, then

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:19.839
I need to know to call isolate around that.

00:04:19.839 --> 00:04:24.519
So not calling isolate when I don't want a reactive relationship, that would be a bug

00:04:24.519 --> 00:04:26.480
in this code, right?

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:34.119
But if I don't have that bug, if I, my relationship with my immediate things that I depend on

00:04:34.119 --> 00:04:38.720
is correct, then I'm satisfied that this piece of code is correct.

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:42.480
And now I can go look at another piece of code and make sure that it's correct.

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:49.760
The bottom line being, if you have an app that's written out of 10 such pieces of code,

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:53.079
then you have to make sure that 10 pieces of code are correct.

00:04:53.079 --> 00:04:57.519
And if you add an 11 piece of code, you have to make sure that 11 piece of code is correct.

00:04:57.519 --> 00:05:02.880
As opposed to having to make sure that each piece of code and all of the possible interactions

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:06.040
it could ever have with any of the rest of the pieces.

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:08.359
Like now that's not 10 things you need to check.

00:05:08.359 --> 00:05:10.880
It's like 10 factorial or something like that, right?

00:05:10.880 --> 00:05:16.799
Or I don't know what the map is, but it is something that's certainly non-linear in terms

00:05:16.799 --> 00:05:21.559
of each additional thing you add, you now have to check all these, all the possible

00:05:21.559 --> 00:05:23.279
things that it could interact with.

00:05:23.279 --> 00:05:27.440
Oh my gosh, I'm going to add a new thing and it's going to be so complicated to know whether

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:32.000
this is going to blow up something that, you know, I already have.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:37.200
That was the world that we lived in before reactivity, when it came to writing interactive

00:05:37.200 --> 00:05:38.200
UIs.

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:41.720
This might go nowhere, but I think when people think about the Lego analogy, which like that

00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:44.720
comes up a lot when you talk about components in software, right?

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:47.880
Like a lot of people think of them as like Legos.

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:52.839
At a high level, you tend to think, oh, I want the ability to snap anything.

00:05:52.839 --> 00:05:54.519
Anything should be able to snap to anything else, right?

00:05:54.519 --> 00:05:56.959
I just want to take two software components and snap them together.

00:05:56.959 --> 00:06:00.880
I don't get that much pushback on reactivity, like, oh, why didn't you do reactivity this

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:01.880
way?

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:03.760
It's not been that much of it.

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:08.160
I think because it's sufficiently complicated that it's like, it's not the most natural

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:12.519
thing to bike shed on, but modules are like the opposite.

00:06:12.519 --> 00:06:19.640
Like everybody's got an opinion on modules and I mean, for most of the Life of Shiny,

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:25.600
people have had opinions on why I didn't do it the right way, you know, and the right

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:29.700
way meaning something so different to every person.

00:06:30.019 --> 00:06:36.339
One really common refrain was basically, people don't like that you have to pass in, like

00:06:36.339 --> 00:06:41.940
if you have something like a module that takes some kind of input that needs to be provided

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:44.660
from somewhere else in the app, right?

00:06:44.660 --> 00:06:49.260
Like you've got a module that does something with a data frame, but it doesn't itself want

00:06:49.260 --> 00:06:55.380
to have any opinion about what that data frame is or where it came from or how it's specified,

00:06:55.380 --> 00:06:56.380
right?

00:06:56.380 --> 00:06:59.940
It doesn't specialize just on some output or whatever.

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:02.179
How do you communicate with that module?

00:07:02.179 --> 00:07:08.339
How do you tell it, this is the data frame you should use and here's when it changes.

00:07:08.339 --> 00:07:14.739
And the way that works in Shiny modules is when you define the module, you take that

00:07:14.739 --> 00:07:17.220
data frame as an input.

00:07:17.220 --> 00:07:20.859
You take a reactive calculation as an input.

00:07:20.859 --> 00:07:27.500
A lot of people push back on that and they're like, I don't want to have all these things

00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:30.739
that I'm passing into, you know, this Lego brick, right?

00:07:30.739 --> 00:07:34.700
Like why can't all Lego bricks just look the same, right?

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:39.299
I don't want to pass in these four arguments that it needs.

00:07:39.299 --> 00:07:43.339
I just want to give it a dictionary.

00:07:43.339 --> 00:07:44.399
How about that?

00:07:44.399 --> 00:07:47.619
Every module just takes a dictionary and then you just have to put the right things in the

00:07:47.619 --> 00:07:53.059
dictionary and then like, look how clean the code is for snapping together all these

00:07:53.059 --> 00:07:54.059
Legos.

00:07:54.059 --> 00:07:58.420
I just make a dictionary, put some stuff in it and then everybody gets the dictionary

00:07:58.420 --> 00:08:02.339
and oh, I can use the dictionary for both input and output.

00:08:02.339 --> 00:08:07.500
Not only can I get data frames out of it or other, you know, reactive things, I can also

00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:11.540
push values into it and then other modules can consume it.

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:15.880
And look how easy it is to snap these Legos together, right?

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:19.940
This is where it's like, it's not enough that the Legos go together.

00:08:19.940 --> 00:08:22.720
They have to go together correctly, right?

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:27.320
So Lego minifigs have heads and torsos and legs, right?

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:30.079
You can't put a head on the legs directly.

00:08:30.079 --> 00:08:36.880
Like they have to, they only connect one way and those connections are obvious.

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:41.000
With a lot of components, it's actually more like that.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:45.159
You don't want Legos that will snap together whether they belong together or not.

00:08:45.159 --> 00:08:49.320
You actually want it to be very obvious that this thing needs to connect with something

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:50.320
that's like this.

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:51.719
It's more like puzzle pieces.

00:08:51.719 --> 00:08:56.919
So people arguing for, oh, let me just have a dictionary that I pass in.

00:08:56.919 --> 00:09:01.400
What they're really saying is like, oh, it's so annoying putting together this puzzle with

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:03.000
all the pieces are all jagged.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.000
Wouldn't it be easier if they were all just squares?

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.919
Like let me make this, you know, put together this 500 piece puzzle, but it'll be so much

00:09:09.919 --> 00:09:12.799
easier if they're all just squares, you know?

00:09:13.239 --> 00:09:16.799
It is actually, you're actually making it so much harder, right?

00:09:16.799 --> 00:09:19.960
Because that problem still exists.

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:27.479
Like you still need to make sure that that data frame that you need is provided to you.

00:09:27.479 --> 00:09:31.400
It's just now provided in a very hidden way that you'd have to go seek out that's not

00:09:31.400 --> 00:09:32.559
obvious.

00:09:32.559 --> 00:09:35.760
So you've removed the signal of how these things connect.

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:40.840
You've removed these sort of weirdly shaped borders and replace them with flat borders,

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:45.359
even though they can really still only connect in one way, if that makes sense.

00:09:45.359 --> 00:09:52.320
So again, just another example of that principle of small pieces that we can locally reason

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:56.039
about and then combine them in reliable ways.

00:09:56.039 --> 00:10:00.719
And when we have just like these dictionaries that we pass around, it's removing that part

00:10:00.719 --> 00:10:03.280
of like, we need to be able to combine these reliably.

00:10:06.359 --> 00:10:10.599
There's so many different ways I want to answer this question.

00:10:10.599 --> 00:10:14.200
Only between building the front end and the back end, I don't think there's a right order.

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:20.080
If what is going to get you excited about the project enough to sort of build that momentum

00:10:20.080 --> 00:10:26.280
is that you have this cool UI concept in mind, or that just motivates you to look at something

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:32.039
concrete and see it sort of one piece after another light up, absolutely go crazy with

00:10:32.039 --> 00:10:33.039
the UI first.

00:10:33.039 --> 00:10:36.679
You know, I don't think there's anything wrong with that.

00:10:36.679 --> 00:10:43.919
If instead like you really have some kind of R code on a server that you're really excited

00:10:43.919 --> 00:10:49.359
to see come to life for the first time and that is going to be what excites you and propels

00:10:49.359 --> 00:10:54.559
you through the rest of the project, I don't think that there is a wrong way to do it.

00:10:54.559 --> 00:11:01.479
If you want to end up with a bunch of well-named, well-reasoned, nicely factored reactives and

00:11:01.479 --> 00:11:07.039
outputs and whatever, is that something you sort of do on a whiteboard first and then

00:11:07.039 --> 00:11:10.119
sort of stub each one out and make it so?

00:11:10.119 --> 00:11:14.119
Or is it more something that you just start coding and then extract out the things that

00:11:14.119 --> 00:11:15.119
you need?

00:11:15.119 --> 00:11:17.039
Again, I don't think there's a wrong way to do it.

00:11:17.039 --> 00:11:23.960
But I would draw a direct analogy to when you're writing either a package or maybe a

00:11:23.960 --> 00:11:25.520
complicated script.

00:11:25.520 --> 00:11:27.760
When and how do you introduce functions?

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:33.119
Because it's exactly the same process that applies here as well, I think.

00:11:33.119 --> 00:11:37.760
Maybe it's a little bit more urgent because it's not going to react unless you find somewhere

00:11:37.760 --> 00:11:41.520
to park this code that is, you know, reactive.

00:11:41.520 --> 00:11:44.719
So in that sense, yeah, you are going to be forced to confront it.

00:11:44.719 --> 00:11:50.880
But some people might write straight line code that's, you know, I'm just going to get

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:54.840
this thing working and get the answer I want and then let me take a step back and see where

00:11:54.840 --> 00:11:58.200
are opportunities to refactor and turn into functions.

00:11:58.200 --> 00:12:01.080
I think that's probably the most common, right?

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:07.159
And for that reason, you might go a long time without ever learning how to write functions

00:12:07.159 --> 00:12:12.039
if your job is more about finding that answer the one time and then moving on.

00:12:12.039 --> 00:12:15.619
So I would call that sort of like a bottom up approach, right?

00:12:15.619 --> 00:12:19.559
You've got the logic and then now you're trying to extract structure out of it.

00:12:19.559 --> 00:12:24.679
I think that's probably the more common way people think their brains work.

00:12:24.679 --> 00:12:29.760
I happen to be the other way, whereas I will start with if I could wave a magic wand and

00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:35.960
have whatever functions I need to exist, if they could exist, what little piece of code

00:12:35.960 --> 00:12:39.239
would I write that would solve the problem that I have here?

00:12:39.239 --> 00:12:45.239
So for some really simple example, I might say, I'm going to wave my magic wand and say

00:12:45.239 --> 00:12:47.940
load data set, remove outliers and clean.

00:12:47.940 --> 00:12:50.039
Maybe that's another function.

00:12:50.039 --> 00:12:56.520
And then let me, you know, generate a set of outputs using these two functions that

00:12:56.520 --> 00:12:58.359
I wish existed.

00:12:58.359 --> 00:13:01.000
And I will just call them even though they don't exist.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:02.200
And then I will stub them out.

00:13:02.200 --> 00:13:04.760
So that's working exactly the opposite way.

00:13:04.760 --> 00:13:06.919
Like I'm calling functions that don't exist.

00:13:06.919 --> 00:13:11.400
And each of those functions is potentially going to call functions that don't exist until

00:13:11.400 --> 00:13:15.140
eventually they start calling functions that exist, right?

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:21.780
And then you basically create a skeleton for the structure first and then fill out,

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:23.739
you know, go back and fill out all the pieces.

00:13:23.739 --> 00:13:29.700
If you can get to this place either way of small components that you can individually

00:13:29.700 --> 00:13:35.580
reason about and combine them reliably, that's ultimately what matters.

00:13:35.580 --> 00:13:41.140
So yeah, in this second, like the top down way where you write, you call the functions

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:49.380
that you wish existed, making sure that they're functions that you want to be, well, functional,

00:13:49.380 --> 00:13:50.380
right?

00:13:50.380 --> 00:13:53.979
You tend to want them not to use global state if you can help it.

00:13:53.979 --> 00:13:58.020
I guess in the Python world, it might be classes that you wish existed.

00:13:58.020 --> 00:14:00.099
You new up an object that doesn't exist yet.

00:14:00.099 --> 00:14:02.739
You call methods that don't exist.

00:14:02.739 --> 00:14:04.940
And then you can go back and fill those things out.

00:14:04.940 --> 00:14:10.020
It is harder to do the top down if it's an unfamiliar domain.

00:14:10.020 --> 00:14:14.380
Like I think the more speculative and the more like, oh my gosh, how is this even going

00:14:14.380 --> 00:14:15.380
to work?

00:14:15.380 --> 00:14:18.700
The harder it is to go that sort of top down approach.

00:14:18.700 --> 00:14:23.580
So I'll sometimes go the top down approach until I realize, oh, I'm way out over my skis

00:14:23.580 --> 00:14:24.580
here.

00:14:24.580 --> 00:14:26.460
I don't actually know how any of this technology works.

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:32.419
Let me go back and do a bunch of bottom up experiments and sort of just work with these

00:14:32.419 --> 00:14:37.219
libraries I've never worked with or this kind of data that I've never seen before.

00:14:37.419 --> 00:14:45.859
And once you start to get a sense of confidence about how the problem is going to be solved,

00:14:45.859 --> 00:14:52.059
then I might switch over to, okay, let me go back to this approach of top down.

00:14:52.059 --> 00:14:56.500
So the same thing I think for shiny apps, I tend to think top down.

00:14:56.500 --> 00:15:02.179
So if I'm looking at a dashboard that I want to build and it's going to have these four

00:15:02.179 --> 00:15:06.580
inputs, I think, what data am I going to need for that?

00:15:06.580 --> 00:15:07.580
Right?

00:15:07.580 --> 00:15:11.979
Oh, I'm going to have to do a bunch of aggregations in order to get that data.

00:15:11.979 --> 00:15:16.099
Do I also need to access the unaggregated data for other things in the app?

00:15:16.099 --> 00:15:21.380
Well, if so, then I really want to make sure that those are both things that are exposed

00:15:21.380 --> 00:15:26.700
as not functions in this case, but reactive calculations.

00:15:26.700 --> 00:15:32.619
And then I feel like the relationship between the inputs and the reactive calculations,

00:15:32.619 --> 00:15:34.739
I tend not to even think about that at all.

00:15:34.739 --> 00:15:36.739
Like that just sort of happens.

00:15:36.739 --> 00:15:40.859
I call the things that I need and then they end up depending on them, unless there's some

00:15:40.859 --> 00:15:46.219
very specific reason, like, you know, I'm going to use this slider input to inform this

00:15:46.219 --> 00:15:48.460
calculation, but not till this button is pressed.

00:15:48.460 --> 00:15:49.460
Okay, fine.

00:15:49.460 --> 00:15:52.059
Then you use an event, you know, for that.

00:15:52.099 --> 00:15:57.140
I can't relate sometimes when people say to me like, oh, there's all these like problems

00:15:57.140 --> 00:16:03.820
with my reactivity and I don't, I have a really hard time keeping track of what inputs are

00:16:03.820 --> 00:16:05.900
being referenced by what reactives.

00:16:05.900 --> 00:16:08.900
I'm sort of like, why do you need to keep track?

00:16:08.900 --> 00:16:13.400
Like it's not about keeping track of the global graph.

00:16:13.400 --> 00:16:19.780
So it's really about each individual reactive only accessing the things that it needs.

00:16:19.780 --> 00:16:21.140
That's the way I approach it.

